1 Introduction

In the Standard Model (SM) of strong and electroweak interactions the gauge couplings to lepton fields are flavour independent. This is a well known property of the SM gauge interactions which is usually called Lepton Flavour Universality (LFU). Among the various processes that can be used to test LFU, are the flavour changing decays involving quark fields such as bâ†’sâ€‹â„“+â€‹â„“âˆ’â†’ğ‘ğ‘ superscriptâ„“superscriptâ„“b\to s\ell^{+}\ell^{-} where â„“Â±superscriptâ„“plus-or-minus\ell^{\pm} stand for eÂ±,Î¼Â±,Ï„Â±superscriptğ‘’plus-or-minussuperscriptğœ‡plus-or-minussuperscriptğœplus-or-minuse^{\pm},\mu^{\pm},\tau^{\pm} leptons. Recent experimental resultsÂ [1] indicate violations of LFU which may be due to a new neutral boson Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime}Â [2, 3] which both changes quark flavour, namely bâ†’sâ†’ğ‘ğ‘ b\rightarrow s, and couples predominantly to muons rather than electrons, with left-handed quark and lepton couplings preferredÂ [4]. The flavourful Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} models are many and varied. One attractive possibility is to consider a vector-like family with non-universal Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} families which mixes with the three chiral families of quarks and leptons with universal Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} couplings, thereby introducing non-universality by the back doorÂ [5]Â 444Extensive references to other non-universal Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} models are also included inÂ [5]..

It is commonly believed that the SM is not the final theory of fundamental interactions, but just an effective low energy limit of some (partially) grand unified theory (GUT), possibly embedded in a string scenario, leading to new physics phenomena and deviations from the SM predictions. For example, new gauge bosons Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} associated with additional abelian symmetries arise from such string embeddingsÂ [2]. Within the framework of F-theoryÂ [8] there are many such extra gauged abelian symmetriesÂ [9], which however are normally assumed to be broken at the high energy scale. Usually these gauge bosons are assumed to have universal couplings to quarks and leptonsÂ [10], however there is no reason in principle from the point of view of F-theory why this should be the case. Despite this there has been no systematic study of non-universal Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} gauge bosons at the low energy scale arising from F-theory to our knowledge.

Motivated by the above recent hints for non-universality, we make a first systematic study of anomaly-free non-universal Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} models arising from F-theory. From a phenomenological point of view, we refer to such models as fluxed GUTs. These models assume a set of rules extracted from F-theory and which can form the basis for a phenomenological analysis of models. In particular we shall use these rules to search for a set of anomaly free modelsÂ 555For recent anomaly free models with non-universal Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime}- couplings seeÂ [6, 7]. in which the low energy effective theory consists of the Minimal Supersymmetric Standard Model (MSSM) augmented by an extra gauged Uâ€‹(1)â€²ğ‘ˆsuperscript1â€²U(1)^{\prime} group broken at the TeV scale, together allowing also for a possible vector-like family at that scale. We shall discover that none of the models with a minimal low energy matter spectrum is capable of explaining the recent B-physics anomalies, while it is possible to account for these anomalies by allowing an extra vector-like family as in [5].

The layout of the paper is as follows. In section two we introcude the notion of fluxed GUTs which are based on essential features playing instrumental rÃ´le in local F-theory constructions. In particular, we describe the rÃ´le of fluxes on the breaking of the gauge symmetry, the splitting of GUT representations and the fermion chirality. In section three we implement these rules to construct Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5SU(5) GUTs with additional abelian symmetries allowing non-universal couplings to fermions. We focus on specific models where both Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5SU(5) GUT and abelian symmetries are embedded in E8subscriptğ¸8E_{8} and formulate the anomaly cancellation conditions which constrain the spectrum of the emerging effective models. In section four we present the solutions of these conditions and classify them according to the properties of the resulting light particle spectrum. We first present characteristic examples of Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5SU(5) with the minimal supersymmetric spectrum having non-universal couplings with the extra Uâ€‹(1)ğ‘ˆ1U(1). We also show solutions containing vector-like fermions with non-universal couplings and discuss their implications to low energy physics. In section five we present our conclusions.

We stress that this particular string theory framework provides the appropriate tools for a natural inclusion of abelian gauge bosons with non-universal gauge couplings to fermions. 6 Conclusions

In this work, we have presented a class of fluxed Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5SU(5) GUTs which naturally incorporate an abelian symmetry, Uâ€‹(1)â€²ğ‘ˆsuperscript1â€²U(1)^{\prime}, where the associated gauge boson Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} displays non-universal gauge couplings to fermion families. This paper represents the first study of non-universal Zâ€²superscriptğ‘â€²Z^{\prime} gauge bosons in F-theory phenomenology. In our analysis we have considered an F-theory inspired framework where Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5SU(5) GUT emerges as a subgroup of the maximal exceptional gauge symmetry E8âŠƒSâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)Ã—Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)âŸ‚ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5ğ‘†ğ‘ˆsubscript5perpendicular-tosubscriptğ¸8E_{8}\supset SU(5)\times SU(5)_{\perp}. Non-trivial universal fluxes are assumed along the Cartan generators of the custodial group factor, Uâ€‹(1)âŸ‚4âŠ‚Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)âŸ‚ğ‘ˆsuperscriptsubscript1perpendicular-to4ğ‘†ğ‘ˆsubscript5perpendicular-toU(1)_{\perp}^{4}\subset SU(5)_{\perp}, breaking the symmetry and generating chirality of the Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5SU(5) spectrum. A ğ’µ2subscriptğ’µ2{\cal Z}_{2} monodromy is imposed which allows rank-one fermion mass matrices and reduces the original symmetry to Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)Ã—Uâ€‹(1)âŸ‚3ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5ğ‘ˆsuperscriptsubscript1perpendicular-to3SU(5)\times U(1)_{\perp}^{3}, while a hypercharge flux breaks the Sâ€‹Uâ€‹(5)ğ‘†ğ‘ˆ5SU(5) GUT down to the Standard Model and, at the same time, induces the observed fermion chirality to the low energy spectrum. We then assume that the Uâ€‹(1)âŸ‚3ğ‘ˆsuperscriptsubscript1perpendicular-to3U(1)_{\perp}^{3} gauge group is broken to a single non-universal Uâ€‹(1)â€²ğ‘ˆsuperscript1â€²U(1)^{\prime}, by some unspecified Higgsing mechanism.

We have analysed the case where the non-universal Uâ€‹(1)â€²ğ‘ˆsuperscript1â€²U(1)^{\prime} is an anomaly-free linear combination of the remaining three Uâ€‹(1)âŸ‚ğ‘ˆsubscript1perpendicular-toU(1)_{\perp} factors, Uâ€‹(1)â€²=âˆ‘i=13ciâ€‹Uâ€‹(1)âŸ‚,iğ‘ˆsuperscript1â€²superscriptsubscriptğ‘–13subscriptğ‘ğ‘–ğ‘ˆsubscript1perpendicular-toğ‘–U(1)^{\prime}=\sum_{i=1}^{3}c_{i}U(1)_{\perp,i}. We chose a basis where two of Uâ€‹(1)âŸ‚,iğ‘ˆsubscript1perpendicular-toğ‘–U(1)_{\perp,i} symmetries are identified with Uâ€‹(1)ÏˆâˆˆE6ğ‘ˆsubscript1ğœ“subscriptğ¸6U(1)_{\psi}\in E_{6} and Uâ€‹(1)Ï‡âˆˆSâ€‹Oâ€‹(10)ğ‘ˆsubscript1ğœ’ğ‘†ğ‘‚10U(1)_{\chi}\in SO(10) and we formulated the gauge anomaly cancellation conditions in terms of a set of integers Ma,Nbsubscriptğ‘€ğ‘subscriptğ‘ğ‘M_{a},N_{b} introduced to parametrise the universal and hypercharge flux effects. We have scanned for solutions for the three coefficients cisubscriptğ‘ğ‘–c_{i} to determine the multiplicities of the corresponding light spectra in terms of the flux integers Ma,Nbsubscriptğ‘€ğ‘subscriptğ‘ğ‘M_{a},N_{b}. We found a plethora of models which are classified with respect to the nature of the non-universal couplings to fermions and the emergent spectrum. There are several classes of models with the minimal low energy MSSM spectrum, as well as several classes with additional vector-like fields.

In particular we highlight the phenomenologically promising classes with universal couplings to the three chiral fermion generations with only the single vector-like family having non-universal couplings. When the vector-like family mixes with the chiral families, non-universality involving the mixed light states may result. Such models naturally suppress New Physics contributions and models can be found which are universal in the the first two light quark families, compatible with known processes such as the K0âˆ’KÂ¯0superscriptğ¾0superscriptÂ¯ğ¾0K^{0}-\bar{K}^{0} mixing, while involving non-universality in the third family. In principle these types of models may alter the branching ratios of the BğµB-decays in accordance with the recently observed deficit in the Î¼+â€‹Î¼âˆ’superscriptğœ‡superscriptğœ‡\mu^{+}\mu^{-} channel. We discuss the plausibility of the above scenario in relation the anomaly cancellation conditions and the scale of the New Physics effects.
